review_blob: bootle from bootle aroma. just a touch of fresh orange squeezed in on accident because glass was near orange juicing process. notes of fresh oranges, bit of fresh squeezed pinked graped fruit. pleasant pineapple and passionfruit. light lactic cream. low bitterness on the juicy tangerine hopes. light lemon yogurt tartness. pleasant level of dryness. nice balance. seems more drinkable just now than when i had it 6 months ago maybe. spills fine.

375 bootle. best by 27/01/2015 so maybe like 9 months old. nobody. 

bright, twangy under-ripened plum and sour grapes. a bit heavy handed on the sour scale. too much lemony sourness detracts from the drinkability, as long sipes could lead to puckering. 

pleasant, fun, enjoyable funk, with notes of soft cowhide leather. rustic musty cheesecloth cellar. 

pretty dry. low carbonation. 

a lot of potential, with some fun leathery funk and nice fruit character. But all of the good things are somewhat dominated by the sharp lemon yogurt sourness. good, but could be more drinkable.
beer_name: Oude Quetsche Tilquin  lAncienne avec Prunes de Namur

review_blob: UPDATED: OCT 4, 2015

Bootle. Gold ale pour. Aroma of Soft Belgium ale pear and apricot fruit with a fun musty hay presence. Quite nice. Spritzy twangy minerally lemon lime and fresh cut grass on that taste tip. Perhaps a touch too much harsh grassy bitterness on that lingering finish, but takes down as it warms down from bier fridge temp.  A fine dry rustic complex hoppy belgianed ale that is @ drinkable.
stout thank you adam chandler for the bootle! strong boozy mead port. sweet prune milk chocolate. grape drank and syzuryp on that lingering finish. boozy chocolately cough syrup. potent. great brew

Deep dive into the rotter for this 2009 reserve barley wine gold ale. Rich toffee. Raisin rum cake. Musty sherry. Oxidized grape drank. Bit of sharp coffee medicine. Better than expected given what was in front of me. Rotted just fine.

6.5 year old bottle. Found during rotbox dive prior to big move. Pours a reddish copper brown hue. So little head an english shiremane would be proud. Aroma offers sweet figgy berry sherry. Twangy raisin and ripened plums. Bit of grape drank cough syrup. Attenuated enough to be reasonably drinkable. A bit oxidized. Lowish carbonation, but enough fizz for the style. Not a favorite style of mine, and from an old bottle stored in less than ideal conditions. Better than expected.
this is a bottle. sweet raisin plum sherry dough bread malts. spicy fruity rum cake. okay for what it is, but what it is is not where i would like to be @.

Barley wine from the rotter this one is from dasilky. Pours poop pond brown with no head offered. Sweet grapey port wine. Grape drank. Dimetap. Potent sweet plummy figs. Touch of metallic acidic character. Perhaps a bit too sweet and medicinal.

Bootle. Creamy gold ale pour with a big tall fizzy soap bubble head. Potent earthy wet leaves. Earthy forest Creamed wheat. Weird metallic note. Banana as well. Bit of spritzy carbonation. Attenuation seems fine enough for a witbier where I am @. Somewhat drinkable, but not very drinkable or memorable in a good way. Scooped just the same.
beer_name: Le Trou du Diable Blanche de Shawi

review_blob: 2009 vintage bootle consumed in 2015. Muddy murky pond water pour with some bonus floaties. Sweet sherry toffee grape drank. Overly sweet sugary metallic plum rumcake. Harsh cough syrup. Gross maybe.

Bootle. Not much of a saison. Weird sweet candied apricots. Swedish fish gummies. Apple cider vinegar. Cidery dumpster nectarines and white grapes. Bit of vinegar bubble gum perfume. Not all bad, but some fowl things are quite the distraction. Petes $e.
Fresh bottle. Bright tart lemoned minerally yogurt. Musty rustic morning wet grassy field. Foggy airy minerally forest stream. Bit of white grapes. Moderately tart. Pleasant dryness. Neat. Fun. Pete.
beer_name: Oxbow / Birrificio del Ducato Saison dellAragosta

review_blob: matured bootle thank you to phaleslu for sending this my way! clear ruby red hu. bit of sherry oxidation. plums, raisins, date fruit character. moderately sweet toffee. on the sweet side, but good enough attenuation on a barley wine gold style ale. not the type of bier i typically reach for these days, but this @ drinkable for a sipes on a night cape sized pour.

bootle thank you macboot! rustic wild flowers, foggy farm air. a bit musty, minerally. soft perfume. fun peach, banana, pear fruit, complimented by a zesty lemon lime zest citrus character. spritzy carbonation. downside: a bit of bitter resiny hops and acidic sulfury cider on the lingering finish could be let outside. but a fun, multi-dimensional bretty hoppy rustic belgium ale. a lot of pieces, but fit together reasonably well. nicely attenuated. with each sipe, you can drink a different bier as you shift focus. peteable.

Boot ul. Big potent bubblicious bubble gum. fruity papaya. peppermint. A little bit of lemon cleaner. Minerally. Tropical fruits.   Mango.  Hint of lemon.  Dry resin cate mint on that linger finish.  Lush effervescent soft mouthfeel. Pleasantly dry. A soft spritzy notable carbonation. Not loving the bubblegummed pear with doughy perfume. But is fun to drink . And is a scoop.

Waxed bootle. Thanks Andy! Pours brown with ruby red on offer as the sun shins through. Small tan fizzy head fades with some quickness. Potent aroma of tangy slightly sour Apple cider, sherry like oxidation, twangy plums. Grape skins. Green apple. Light perfume. Okay. Tastes like an uli blend of impy tart Apple cider, 5 year old closet aged barley wine, small portion of red wine, dash of nail polish. Somewhat of a hodgepodge, but better than expected given the scores. Much more drinkable than orange scorpion. But not something I would turn to if I was looking to drink a bier to bfrank.
beer_name: CIB Barleys Angels Barrel Aged Imperial Wild Ale

review_blob: bottle. lush dark potent cherry fruit. soft leather. light vinous dry oak. red semi sweet strawberries, raspberry, cherry wine. soft musty dusty cellar. well balanced all around with a pleasantly dry mouthfeel complimented by semi sweet berry fruit. fun wine, fruit juice, beer combo. not much in the way of tripel character, which is just fine. more of an impy fruit forward sour cherry brew. tame.
UPDATED: JUL 4, 2015
Tap. Citrusy bright juicy grapefruit. Soft light juicy clementine. Soft herbs. Dry. Tame Pete.
Tap. Harsh resin bitterness. Some weird dough. Harsh grapefruit. Not all that drinkable.
UPDATED: JUL 7, 2015
beer_name: Hill Farmstead Works of Love (Earl Grey Tea)

review_blob:
Excited to try this gold ale as I loved Maine beer Juan. Also 4.7 percent hopped gold ale is right in my wheel baus if it is done nicely and I have quite a bit of confidence in Maine beer co to do a fine job. That may mean that I am a homer no one knows. 

Anyways, the gold ale has big potent juicy tropical fruit hops of pineapple, tangerine, clementine. Some fresh juicy peaches. Lifts quite a bit. Very inviting. Hint of grapefruit, pine bitterness but quite restrained and balanced nicely by the juiced up tropical fruit sweetness. If one hop stands out amongst all the hops used it is perhaps the Nelsen sauvin maybe. Perfectly moderately dry. Very pleasant combination of freshly squeezed tropical fruits, oranges, pineapple with a hint of grapefruit zest to make things interesting. No booze notes. Pleasant neutral malt backing lets hops bo shine. This is a fun juicy chuggable tame Pete to be sure.
Bottle. Potent ripe Pear, honeysuckle, Melon. Doughy Earthy creamed wheat. Effervescent. Similar essence to Orval I suppose. Drinkable.
Bottle poured into gold ale glass. Bright lemon, tangerine, melon pine. Light honey sweetness provides some balance. Bitter citrusy grapefruit lingering finish. Pretty dry. Pretty drink. Chugs fine.

Bottled rew thank you to Pepsican for the hook up. Pours hazed gold ale. Moderate to heavy clean refreshing lemony yogurt cream sourness. Light soft wheat essence. Not too thin not to big on that body just fine. Not much bad to say. No weird off flavor a that you sometimes get in a Berliner Weiss type brew, but no interesting funk which is fine. A clean bright lemony yogurt wheat bier that is @ drinkable.

Bottle andy. Consumed for Frank (birthday) and Frank (puge(8)). Juicy complex passion fruit, clementines, grap fruit, cateminte. Towards the upper bound of the pleasant bitterness range. Which is fine. A welcomed tiny bite. Somewhat muddled juicy tropical fruit parfait and resin taste. Moderate dryness is nice. Not the cleanest bier but tasty juicy lot going on and drinkable. Thanks piper for the courtesy.
chalky old cardboard vanilla bourbon play dough. Weird doughy sweetness. Petes bucke.
beer_name: Labatt Prohibition Series Bourbon Barrel Ale

review_blob: bootle. lemon yogurt. white grape and apricot. light oak. moderate dryness. moderate carbonation. drinkable.
can from hammer slammer chuged from can. herbal, pine hop. bit of resiny bitterness. lightly earthy caramel biscuit. somewhat drinkable.
thank you andy for the gold. bit of resin pine. mango, tropical fruit. bit too much bitterness. bit too much malty sweetness. hop character not particularly exciting. lingering cred finish.

Bootle pours like a creamed yellow gold ale with a frothy Juan inch head. Bright fresh rustic herbs and Lemon grass hops backed by a nice dry cracker malt.  pleasant Mineral presence. Moderate wet grass hop bitterness. Quite dry. Very bright dry crisp refreshing effervescent bier. Crushable saison light with less harsh bitterness and all of the flavor a jocky could ask for. Petes like hazel grace.
beer_name: De la Senne Crushable de Table

review_blob: On tape. Clean gold ale. Herbal grassy hop presence. Semisweet biscuit and dough malts. ChuggAble.

review_blob: Solid double on tape. Juicy Tropical fruits . Pineapple. But of resin bitterness. Pleasant moderate dryness. Bitterness in check. Petes tame.
Bright pine and herbal hops. Lime. Good deal of resin. Dry. Perhaps a bit too bitter. Faint biscuit malts. Somewhat drinkable.
Bright pot my pine needles Christmas trees spruce . Little in the way of malt presence. Dry. Not too bitter. Fine.
Tap. Roasty toasty porter with a vinous red grape twang. Moderate drynesS. Not huge fan of soured dark brews in general but this poured okay.
Pours like a gold ale on tap @ brewpube. Bright sweaty lemongrass. Melon sweetness provides some balance. White wine oak. Bit of perfume. Moderate dryness. Okay.
Tapped @ brewpube. Creamy wheat. Light to moderate spice. Highly effervescent. Cream soda wheat brew with bright fizzy carbonation and light coriander spice.
UPDATED: MAY 23, 2015
Tap @ the pube. Herbal moderately bitter grass and pine. Mineral grainy dry cracker. Brouch too bitter. Dry. Hop character nothing to write to baus about. Somewhat drinkable.

bootle. pleasant wheat malt backing with a bit of biscuit character. low to moderate sourness. yogurt with a touch of lemongrass. peteable pear fruit and a bit of earthy doughy forest fog. moderate carbonation, dryness. seems like half soured ale and half bretty belgiumed ale. all the individual pieces are kind of neat, but would perhaps like this to be split into two separate beers. drinkable.
UPDATED: MAY 8, 2015

Bottle. Bit of honey kissed tart yogurt sour brew. Apricot fruit. White wine . Like a Anna and mimosa blend with some pleasant white grape character, apricots, lemon, bit of old musty wood funk. Dry. Petes tame.

bootle poured into xnobe glass. color is of a creamed corn golden ale. aroma is soft floral hibiscus wheat with a bronus tipe of musty fog. Hint of leafy lemon. fizzy mouthfeel and is also @ mosty dry. oop vir.

Tap offering @ armsby abbey. Big juicy fresh clementines. Hint of fresh peach. Complex juicy tropical fruit, bit of white grape, peaches. Lightest hint of grapefruit. Potent inviting aroma. Dry. The beer lifts.

review_blob: bottle thank you to glouglouburp for this "complex aroma of fruit, alcohol and hops" beer. 2009 on the ribbon and properly stored in kitchen cupboard till 2015. aroma of big sweet boozy rum cake, figs, dates. bit of dimetap. alcohol soaked date/fig/over ripened plum fruit with a licorice and cough syrup pete. mellowed out. not overly sweet. only big gripe is the cough syrup presence, otherwise warming and somewhat drinkable.
